<p><b>Simon Baron-Cohen</b> is Professor of <a href="/w/index.php?title=Developmental_Psychopathology&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Developmental Psychopathology (page does not exist)">Developmental Psychopathology</a> in the Departments of <a href="/wiki/Psychiatry" title="Psychiatry">Psychiatry</a> and <a href="/wiki/Experimental_Psychology" title="Experimental Psychology" class="mw-redirect">Experimental Psychology</a>, a Fellow of <a href="/wiki/Trinity_College,_Cambridge" title="Trinity College, Cambridge">Trinity College, Cambridge</a>, and Director of the Autism Research Centre at the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Cambridge" title="University of Cambridge">University of Cambridge</a>, in the <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom" title="United Kingdom">United Kingdom</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> He is best known for his work on <a href="/wiki/Autism" title="Autism">autism</a>, including his early theory that autism involves degrees of "<a href="/wiki/Mind-blindness" title="Mind-blindness">mindblindness</a>" (or delays in the development of <a href="/wiki/Theory_of_mind" title="Theory of mind">theory of mind</a>); and his later theory that autism is an extreme form of the "male brain", which involved a reconceptualization of typical psychological sex differences in terms of <a href="/wiki/Empathizing%E2%80%93systemizing_theory" title="Empathizing–systemizing theory">empathizing–systemizing theory</a>.</p>
